result.execSummary:
The defendant Donovan A. Cunningham was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Receiving Stolen Property >$5000 - $10,000 or Firearm [Modifiers: Habitual Criminality], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.34(1)(bm).
  • Receiving Stolen Property >$5000 - $10,000 or Firearm [Modifiers: Habitual Criminality], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.34(1)(bm).
  • Receiving Stolen Property >$5000 - $10,000 or Firearm [Modifiers: Habitual Criminality], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.34(1)(bm).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The restitution and costs have been paid from defendant's bond.
Defendant shall submit to a DNA sample at the Taylor County Sheriff's Department.

Defendant shall write a letter of apology to the victims due within 30 days of sentencing and preapproved by probation.  Defendant shall undergo any other counseling as deemed appropriate by probation.    Defendant shall pay supervision fees as ordered by the Department of Corrections. 
If probation is ordered and ultimately revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA and follow through with all treatment recommendations.

Defendant Donovan A. Cunningham in court with attorney Daniel Francis Snyder.  Kristi S. Tlusty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Plea agreement put into the record.  Victim rights complied with.  State moves to amend counts 1 thru 3 to Felony Concealing Stolen Property as a Repeater - 943.34.  Defendant enters a plea of no contest to the amended charges.  Plea colloquy.  Plea freely, voluntarily and intelligently; factual basis exists.  Court finds defendant guilty of the amended charges.  Statements by Attorney Tlusty, Attorney Snyder and defendant.  Court orders withheld sentence - probation for four years with conditions of court costs on each count; DNA sample and surcharge.  Surcharge is count 1 only.  Restitution joint and several; letter of apology to the victims due within 30 days of plea and sentencing and preapproved by probation.  AODA and follow all treatment recommendations; any other counseling as deemed appropriate by probation.   - rt
